    M1 -.-> MQ1["What did you personally own end to end, and where did your ownership stop?"] & MQ2["What were the hardest tradeoffs you made to keep this production-shaped instead of academically ideal?"]
    M2 -.-> MQ4["What evidence would you show first if a skeptical hiring manager said, 'this still sounds like a polished project'?"]
    M3 -.-> MQ3["What part of this work most clearly separates you from someone who only built a pipeline or trained a model?"]
    MQ1 --> MR1["I owned the system truth path end to end: the governed fraud world beneath it, the shared runtime and learning path above it, the readiness program that turned it from wired into earned, and the current operating layer above that ready system. My ownership stopped at the proof boundary itself, which is why I do not quietly overclaim beyond what the platform has actually earned."]
    MQ2 --> MR2["The hardest tradeoffs were choosing governed, managed, and auditable paths over cleaner-looking shortcuts. That meant one shared operating world instead of separate datasets, managed learning surfaces instead of local convenience, and explicit rollback, cost, incident, and audit controls instead of optimistic progress."]
    MQ3 --> MR3["The clearest separator is that I did not stop at data flow or model output. I had to own the governed world beneath the system, the platform boundaries above it, the readiness proof that made the system operationally believable, the governed model delivery corridor, and the day-2 surfaces that make the whole thing runnable, recoverable, auditable, and cost-real."]
    MQ4 --> MR4["I would show three things first: a governed fraud world with an accepted 331.5M-event slice backed by a 473.4M-event raw horizon, integrated and widened runtime proof at the declared envelope, and operator drills, audit-grade evidence, safe idle and restore, and attributable cost. Those are exactly the things polished projects usually avoid."]
